    {
      "_id": "MPParagraphElement:ECC30005-57C6-4B47-9471-40D86740AB8D",
      "contents": "<p xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" id=\"MPParagraphElement:ECC30005-57C6-4B47-9471-40D86740AB8D\" class=\"MPElement\" data-object-type=\"MPParagraphElement\">Stilbenes belong to natural polyphenols in which two phenyl parts are connected by the methylene of two carbon. Structurally, stilbenes are characterized by the replacement of two benzene rings with hydroxyl and methoxy groups. In general, stilbenes are not as common as other polyphenols, which exist in some plants in the form of glycosylation [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:D4D308C3-78BC-466B-B990-FE6CB99264F1\">142</span>].</p>",
